            <p>ADDRESS LETTERS<lb/>
                L. STRAUS &#38; SONS&#44;<lb/>
                P. O. BOX 1000.<lb/></p>
            <p>Per Steamer&#95;&#95;&#95;&#95;&#95;&#95;&#95;<lb/>
                42&#44; 44&#44; 46&#44; &#38; 48 WARREN ST.&#44; AND 116 CHAMBERS ST.&#44;<lb/></p>
            <p>CABLE ADDRESS&#58; &#40;STRAUS&#44; NEW YORK.&#41;<lb/></p>
            <p>New York Aug. 5&#44; 1897.<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev. Dr. S. Morais&#44;<lb/>
                546 N. 5th St.&#44; Philadelphia&#44; Pa.<lb/>
                My Dear Sir&#58;<lb/></p>
            <p>I beg to acknowledge receipt of<lb/> your favor of the 4th inst. regarding the unauthorized use of<lb/> your name by the President of the Congregation in Kalamazoo&#44;<lb/> Mich.&#44; in his application to Baroness Hirsch.  My name was<lb/> also used in the same manner without authority&#44; and I received<lb/> a similar letter&#44; to which I have sent a very peremptory reply&#44;<lb/> that they had no authority for the use of my name&#44; that I<lb/> entirely disapprove of it&#44; and I have even gone a step fur&#45;<lb/>ther and sent Baroness Hirsch a copy of the correspondence&#59; so<lb/> I think that matter is completely disposed of.<lb/></p>
            <p>I am ashamed of the great abuse by many of my co&#45;<lb/>religionists in this country of the generous disposition of<lb/> Baroness de Hirsch&#44; and have done all in my power to discourage<lb/> such&#44; and I think the Baroness understands the situation.<lb/>  Yours truly&#44;<lb/> Oscar S. Straus<lb/></p>
            </body>
